{"summary":{"verdict":"BLOCK","one_liner":"Timezone-blind cutoff check will approve or reject orders incorrectly for every non-UTC customer, worsening as the platform expands to New York."},"critical_findings":[{"title":"getHours() uses server UTC time, not customer local time","risk":"During British Summer Time (UTC+1), a London customer ordering at 14:30 local time gets orderHour=13 in UTC, passing the check — they receive a same-day delivery promise that cannot be fulfilled. Conversely, a New York customer ordering at 10:00 AM EST (UTC-5) gets orderHour=15, rejected despite being 4 hours before their local cutoff.","severity":"Critical","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable, line: const orderHour = orderTime.getHours()","reproduction":"1. Set server TZ=UTC. 2. Create a Date representing 14:30 BST (13:30 UTC): new Date('2026-06-15T13:30:00Z'). 3. isSameDayDeliveryAvailable returns true — customer is promised same-day delivery after their local cutoff. 4. For New York: new Date('2026-06-15T15:00:00Z') represents 11:00 AM EDT — function returns false, rejecting a valid order.","fix":"Accept or derive the customer's IANA timezone (e.g. 'Europe/London', 'America/New_York'), convert to local hours, then compare. Example:

function isSameDayDeliveryAvailable(orderTimeUTC: Date, customerTZ: string): boolean {
  const cutoffHour = 14;
  const localHour = new Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', {
    hour: 'numeric', hour12: false, timeZone: customerTZ
  }).format(orderTimeUTC);
  return parseInt(localHour, 10) < cutoffHour;
}","time_to_fix":"30 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Orders must be placed before 14:00 LOCAL time for same-day delivery"},{"title":"No validation of the Date input — NaN propagation","risk":"If orderTime is undefined, null, an invalid Date, or a string that wasn't parsed, getHours() returns NaN. NaN < 14 evaluates to false, silently rejecting every order rather than surfacing an error. In a backend service receiving JSON, new Date(undefined) is common when a field is missing.","severity":"High","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable, line: const orderHour = orderTime.getHours()","reproduction":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable(new Date('garbage')) returns false — customer is silently told same-day delivery is unavailable with no error logged.","fix":"Guard the input: if (!(orderTime instanceof Date) || isNaN(orderTime.getTime())) throw new Error('Invalid orderTime');","time_to_fix":"5 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"System must not silently degrade — invalid inputs must produce observable errors"},{"title":"Cutoff is per-hour only — boundary and date-rollover edge cases","risk":"The check ignores the date component entirely. A Date from yesterday at 09:00 UTC passes the check, promising same-day delivery for an order placed in the past. Additionally, the comparison is strictly less-than, meaning an order at exactly 14:00:00.000 is rejected — this may or may not match the business rule ('before 14:00' vs 'by 14:00'), but the ambiguity is unspecified and untested.","severity":"High","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable, full function","reproduction":"const yesterday = new Date(); yesterday.setDate(yesterday.getDate() - 1); yesterday.setUTCHours(9,0,0,0); isSameDayDeliveryAvailable(yesterday) // true — promises same-day for a past order","fix":"Compare orderTime against a full cutoff DateTime (today's date at 14:00 in the customer's timezone) rather than just the hour. Also verify orderTime is today's date in the customer's local calendar.","time_to_fix":"20 minutes","acceptance_criteria_affected":"Same-day delivery must only apply to orders placed today before the cutoff"}],"important_issues":[{"title":"Hardcoded cutoff hour prevents per-region or per-warehouse configuration","description":"As the platform expands to New York (and presumably beyond), different regions may have different cutoff times based on warehouse operations. A hardcoded constant of 14 forces a code change and redeploy for any cutoff adjustment.","location":"const cutoffHour = 14"},{"title":"No logging or metrics on cutoff decisions","description":"In a backend service, same-day delivery eligibility is a critical business decision. There is no logging of the decision outcome, the inputs, or the derived local time — making it impossible to debug customer complaints or audit false promises after the fact.","location":"isSameDayDeliveryAvailable, full function"}],"suggestions":["Use a well-tested timezone library (date-fns-tz, luxon, or Temporal when available) rather than Intl.DateTimeFormat parsing for production-critical time logic","Make the cutoff hour configurable per-region via environment variable or config service","Add unit tests for: BST boundary (last Sunday of March/October), New York EDT/EST transitions, exactly-at-cutoff, invalid inputs, and yesterday's timestamps"],"production_readiness":{"deployment_risks":"Every same-day delivery decision is wrong for non-UTC customers right now. London summer orders will be over-promised; New York orders will be universally under-promised. This is a revenue and trust issue on both sides.","rollback_capability":"Function is stateless — rollback is a code revert with no data migration needed.","backward_compatibility":"Fixing this requires adding a customerTZ parameter, which is a breaking change to the function signature. All callers must be updated to pass timezone.","monitoring_coverage":"None. No logging, no metrics, no alerting on decision rates. A spike in false same-day promises would go undetected.","breaking_changes":{"api_breaking":true,"db_destructive":false,"shared_library":false,"auth_security":false,"data_pipeline":false,"config_changes":true,"details":["Adding required customerTZ parameter changes the function signature — all callers must update","Cutoff should move from hardcoded constant to config"]},"safe_to_deploy":false,"rollback_plan":"Revert to previous version; function is pure/stateless so no state cleanup required"},"escalations":[],"confidence":{"level":95,"high_confidence_areas":["Timezone bug is deterministic and reproducible — getHours() on a UTC server ignoring local time is a textbook defect","Invalid Date propagation is trivially verifiable","Missing date-component check is provable with a one-line test"],"low_confidence_areas":["Business intent on exact-cutoff boundary (< vs <=) — need product confirmation"],"assumptions":["Server runs in UTC as stated","orderTime is constructed from client-submitted or request-received timestamps in UTC","The business rule is 14:00 in the customer's local timezone, not server timezone"]}}

